    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. so if an insect or something gets in there, how does that actually mess with the reading? like does the airspeed indicator just stop working or does it give a wrong number? i'm just worried about how sudden the failure is if something gets stuck in it.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If a blockage occurs, the airspeed indicator doesn't just stop working; it starts giving you a dangerously misleading reading. It's like a tiny, persistent, and very sneaky gremlin hiding in your measurement system! If the pitot tube is blocked, the instrument thinks the total pressure is the same as the static pressure, which means it reads zero dynamic pressure, effectively showing you an airspeed of zero, even if you are flying at a brisk speed.\n\nThe failure can be quite sudden, which is why pre-flight checks are so vital. You need to be vigilant, because a sudden drop to zero when you're cruising is a massive red flag. It's much better to notice a slight wobble or a gradual change, which might suggest a partial blockage, than to suddenly be told you've stopped moving when you're actually flying fast.",
      "source": "target",
